# Config file for generating sample (invoice) data.
# Update any/all fields below that you want.
#
# For any data that gets generated by a distribution,
# we use the following rules:
#   Distribution: One of {NORMAL, UNIFORM, DISCRETE_UNIFORM, POISSON}
#   *_MEAN:
#     - NORMAL:  Mean (\mu)
#     - UNIFORM: Center of range
#     - DISCRETE_UNIFORM: Center of range
#     - POISSON: Mean (\lambda)
#   *_VAR:
#     - NORMAL:  Variance (\sigma^2)
#     - UNIFORM: NA
#     - DISCRETE_UNIFORM: Step-size (use 1.0 for integers)
#     - POISSON: NA
#   *_MAX:
#     - NORMAL:  NA
#     - UNIFORM: Right-most endpoint ('b')
#     - DISCRETE_UNIFORM: Right-most endpoint ('b')
#     - POISSON: NA
#
# NOTES:
#   This script will generate global data for a database, where there are
#   n independent columns and one dependent column. If desired,
#   this script can also partition this "virtual" database into arbitrary
#   verticals, and within each vertical, into various horizontal segments.
#   The dependent column (which is implicitly the *last* column in the *last* vertical)
#   will satisfy:
#    (*)  y = a1 x1 + ... + an xn + noise
#   So we need to specify:
#     1) The total number of intersecting/common observations (rows)
#     2) The noise sample distribution (in (*) above)
#     3) The number of verticals
#         a) For each vertical, the number of rows (must be at least value in (1))
#         b) For each vertical, the number of columns
#            NOTE: Since the dependent variable is always the last column
#            in the last vertical, we won't need to explicitly specify the
#            following for it.
#             i) For each column, the column datatype
#            ii) For each column, the sample distribution
#         b) For each vertical, the number of parties
#             i) For each party, the number of observations
#                Across all parties, this must sum to the value in (3a)
# ==============================================================================

OUTPUT_DIR=.                # Output directory for three json files (can be "." for current dir)
NUM_TOTAL_COLS=4
NUM_TOTAL_COMMON_ROWS=26
NUM_VERTICALS=2

